article.headline: Thomas' 26 points pace Stars
article.linkText: Silver Stars tops Comets to end 9-game slide
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- After nearly two months between victories,
the San Antonio Silver Stars had almost forgotten how good winning
feels.

LaToya Thomas scored a career-high 26 points and the Silver
Stars Antonio snapped a franchise-record nine-game losing streak
Thursday night, beating the Houston Comets 77-72 for their first
win since July 15.

"It's the best feeling in the world," said Thomas, who also
had 10 rebounds. "It's hard to explain how we feel, it's exciting
to win again. We feel like a different team now. It's a weight off
of our shoulders and now we can have a good time out there and be
us."

San Antonio's last win came two weeks before the Olympic break,
a 78-67 victory over Connecticut.

"We gave them a challenge tonight to put together two halves of
play," said interim San Antonio coach Shell Dailey, who picked up
her seventh win as head coach against the Comets. "I'm so proud of
them because they played to their potential, they played the whole
game."

Dailey also served as an interim coach last season.

Adrienne Goodson scored 14 points and Margo Dydek added 13 for
the Silver Stars.

Tina Thompson scored 20 points, Michelle Snow finished with 14
and Sheryl Swoopes added 11 for Houston, which lost its third
straight.

"San Antonio did a great job in the second half," Houston
coach Van Chancellor said. "LaToya Thomas played really well. She
showed why she is going to be a star in this league."

San Antonio outscored the Comets 7-2 in the final two minutes to
seal the win. A jump shot by Semeka Randall gave San Antonio the
lead for good at 72-70 with 1:43 remaining.

Free throws down the stretch by Goodson, Shannon Johnson and
Thomas helped seal the win.

"We're beyond being tired of losing," Goodson said. "We were
at the prayer stage. I think I would have to get a Hallmark to
express my feelings. There aren't any words. I'm glad to get a
win."

Trailing by 11 points at the start of the second half, San
Antonio went on a 19-14 run and took a 52-51 lead on a free throw
by Goodson with 10:58 remaining.

The teams exchanged leads until San Antonio moved ahead 63-59 on
a jump shot by Dydek with 5:56 left.

Houston, helped by four 3-pointers in the second half, reclaimed
the lead at 67-65 on a 3-pointer by Felicia Ragland with 3:41
remaining.

Dydek's first 3-pointer of the season gave the Silver Stars a
70-69 lead with 2:30 to play.

Houston had built an 11-point lead in the opening 20 minutes and
led 37-33 at halftime. Thompson and Snow each scored 10 in the
first half.

"They just look like they wanted it more," Swoopes said.
"They were the more aggressive team and they got more of their
shots to fall in the second half."

Thomas kept San Antonio in the game with 16 first-half points.
